            "text": "The general rule of thumb is to get a professional facial **every 4 to 6 weeks**.\n\nThis timeframe isn't arbitrary; it is designed to align with your skin's natural **cell turnover cycle**, which is the process of your skin shedding dead cells and replacing them with new ones. For most healthy adults, this cycle takes about 28 to 30 days.\n\nHowever, the \"perfect\" frequency depends on your specific skin type, your age, and your skincare goals.\n\n### 1. Frequency by Skin Type\n*   **Oily or Acne-Prone Skin:** **Every 2 to 4 weeks.** During active breakout phases, more frequent sessions (including extractions and light peels) help clear out congestion and bacteria. Once the skin stabilizes, you can move to a monthly maintenance schedule.\n*   **Normal, Dry, or Combination Skin:** **Every 4 to 6 weeks.** A monthly \"reset\" is usually enough to deep-clean pores, remove the month’s buildup of dead skin, and provide professional-grade hydration.\n*   **Sensitive Skin:** **Every 6 to 8 weeks.** Sensitive skin has a more delicate barrier and needs more time to recover between treatments. Over-exfoliating sensitive skin can lead to redness, burning, and increased reactivity.\n\n### 2. Frequency by Age\nAs you age, your skin cell turnover slows down, which can make your complexion look dull or uneven.\n*   **In your 20s:** **Every 6 to 8 weeks.** Focus is on prevention and keeping pores clear.\n*   **In your 30s & 40s:** **Every 4 weeks.** This is when cell turnover begins to slow. Monthly facials that incorporate LED therapy or light chemical peels can help stimulate collagen and maintain a glow.\n*   **50s and Beyond:** **Every 3 to 5 weeks.** Because the natural renewal cycle can stretch to 60+ days at this stage, regular professional treatments are necessary to manually stimulate blood flow and cell regeneration.\n\n### 3. Special Considerations\n*   **Before a Big Event:** If you have a wedding or photo shoot, schedule your facial **3 to 7 days before** the event. This gives any temporary redness or \"purging\" (minor breakouts caused by extractions) time to heal, leaving you with the \"post-facial glow\" on the big day.\n*   **Seasonal Changes:** Many people find they need facials more often during **seasonal transitions**. For example, a hydrating facial in early winter can help combat \"heater skin,\" while a clarifying facial in early summer helps manage increased oil and sweat.\n*   **Budget/Time Constraints:** If monthly isn't realistic, aim for **once a season** (4 times a year). This allows a professional to assess your skin as the weather changes and adjust your at-home product routine accordingly.\n\n### When is it \"Too Much\"?\nGetting facials too frequently (more than once every two weeks) can lead to **over-exfoliation syndrome**. Signs you are overdoing it include:\n*   Shiny but \"tight\" or plastic-looking skin.\n*   Increased sensitivity to products that usually don't bother you.\n*   Persistent redness or a stinging sensation.\n*   Unexpected breakouts (caused by a damaged moisture barrier).\n\n**Summary Tip:** If you are unsure, start with a **4-week interval**. After your first session, a licensed esthetician can analyze your skin’s thickness, oil production, and sensitivity to give you a personalized \"prescription\" for how often to return.",
